Statistical Analysis of GPP

Jaideep Joshi

13-8-2025

Introduction

In this tutorial, we explore the R programming language and tidy data analysis techniques. We will do so through building a statistical model of Gross Primary Productivity (GPP), i.e., the total amount of carbon captured by plants through photosynthesis. The tutorial is structured to guide you step-by-step, starting from loading raw data, tansforming data into various tidy formats, fitting a statistical model for GPP, and performing complex visualizations using the tidyverse ecosystem in R.

By the end of this tutorial, you will have a solid understanding of how to manipulate, visualize, and model data in R.

0. Load Required Libraries

To begin, we load the tidyverse, a collection of R packages designed for data science. The tidyverse includes several powerful tools such as: - ggplot2 for creating elegant data visualizations. - dplyr for data manipulation. - tidyr for reshaping and cleaning data.

library(tidyverse)

2. Tidy data formats (long, wide, and nested)

Before doing any analysis or plotting, its important to understand how data can be organized.

In practice, you will often encounter three common formats:

Wide format

Each variable has its own column, and each row represents one observation in time or space.

Example (conceptually):

date temp vpd ppfd
t1

This format is convenient for regression models, but not ideal for plotting many variables at once.

Long format

Variable names are stored in one column, and their values in another.

Example:

date name value
t1 temp
t1 vpd

Long format is especially useful for:

  • ggplot visualizations
  • faceted plots
  • grouped summaries

Most tidyverse tools expect or work best with long data.

Nested format

Nested data is when a column itself contains a data frame.

Instead of holding numbers directly, a column may hold an entire table per row.

This is common when:

  • data are grouped by site
  • multiple time series are stored together
  • models are stored inside tables

In our case, p_model_drivers contains a column called forcing that holds a small data frame for each site.

Here, we demonstrate how to unnest the forcing column from the drivers dataset, remove unnecessary columns, and convert the data between wide and long formats. This is a crucial step for preparing data for analysis and visualization.

You may notice the symbol |> in the code above. This is called the pipe operator.

The pipe operator takes the result of the expression on its left and automatically passes it as the first argument to the function on its right.

Conceptually, p_model_drivers |> unnest(forcing) is the same as unnest(p_model_drivers, forcing). It means, Take the drivers object, apply the unnest function to it, with forcing as its seconf argument.

Using pipes makes code easier to read because it follows a left-to-right workflow, similar to natural language: Read the data, then show the first rows, then plot, etc.

This style becomes especially powerful when chaining many operations together (reading data cleaning reshaping plotting).

3. Visualize P Model Drivers

Visualization is a powerful tool for understanding data. In this section, we create a line plot to visualize the trend of a single driver variable (e.g., VPD) over time. This helps us identify patterns and anomalies in the data.

p_model_drivers |> 
  unnest(cols=forcing) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=date, y=vpd))+
  geom_line()+
  theme_classic()

Milestone 3: Plot all drivers over time in a multi-faceted plot

To gain a comprehensive view of all driver variables, we create a multi-faceted plot. This involves selecting specific columns, reshaping the data into long format, and using facet_wrap() to create separate panels for each variable.

4. Visualize P Model Validation Data

Here, we visualize the validation dataset in a similar manner. This allows us to compare observed GPP values with the drivers and identify relationships between them.

p_model_validation |> 
  unnest(cols=data) |>
  select(-sitename) |> 
  pivot_longer(-date) |>
  ggplot(aes(x=date, y=value)) +
  geom_line() + 
  facet_wrap(~name, scales = "free_y") +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "Value", title = "P Model Validation Data")

Milestone 4: Plot the uncertainty values as a band around GPP

Uncertainty is an important aspect of any model. Here, we calculate the upper and lower bounds of GPP by adding and subtracting uncertainty values. These bounds are visualized as a shaded ribbon around the GPP line.

5. Combine Drivers and Validation Data

To analyze the relationship between drivers and validation data, we join the two datasets by date. This creates a combined dataset that includes both observed GPP and the corresponding driver variables.

p_model_combined = 
  p_model_drivers |> 
  unnest(cols=forcing) |>
  select(-params_siml, -site_info, -sitename) |> 
  left_join(
    p_model_validation |> 
    unnest(cols=data) |>
    select(date, gpp)
  ) 
## Joining with `by = join_by(date)`

6. Visualize Combined Data

We plot all variables from the combined dataset over time to identify trends and relationships between the drivers and observed GPP.

7. Fit a Linear Model

In this section, we fit a simple linear model to predict GPP based on light (PPFD). This demonstrates the concept of light-use efficiency and provides a baseline for more complex models.

p_model_combined |> 
  ggplot(aes(x=ppfd, y=gpp)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "blue") +
  labs(x = "PPFD", y = "GPP", title = "GPP vs PPFD")  
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 380 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
## (`stat_smooth()`).
## Warning: Removed 380 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

mod = p_model_combined |> 
  with(lm(gpp~ppfd)) 

mod |> broom::tidy()
## # A tibble: 2  5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)     1.32    0.0605      21.8 4.11e- 94
## 2 ppfd         6377.    153.          41.7 1.77e-266

8. Add Predicted GPP to the Data

Using the fitted model, we predict GPP values and add them to the combined dataset. This allows us to compare observed and predicted GPP.

# Add predicted gpp to the combined data
p_model_obs_vs_pred <- p_model_combined |> 
  mutate(gpp_pred = predict(mod, newdata = p_model_combined))

9. Plot Predicted vs Observed GPP

Finally, we assess the models performance by plotting predicted GPP against observed GPP. A perfect model would result in points lying along the red diagonal line.

p_model_obs_vs_pred |>
  ggplot(aes(x = gpp, y = gpp_pred)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red") +
  labs(
    x = "Observed GPP",
    y = "Predicted GPP",
    title = "Predicted vs Observed GPP: LUE model"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
## Warning: Removed 380 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).
